[1] Northern leaf blight, southern rust, nematodes, maize - Georgia
Date: Thu 18 Mar 2010
Source: Southeast Farm Press [edited]
<http://southeastfarmpress.com/grains/corn-diseases-0318/>


Northern leaf blight threatens Georgia corn
-------------------------------------------
Georgia Extension Plant Pathologist Bob Kemerait warns corn growers to
get ready to fight damaging diseases in their 2010 crops.

"Southern rust can devastate non-resistant hybrids," says Kemerait.
"It has been the no. 1 disease on Georgia corn until last year [2009].
The spores don't over-winter here, but they are carried in the winds
from Mexico, the Caribbean, and Central America." A new race showed up
in 2008 that successfully attacked [previously] resistant hybrids.

Last year [2009], northern corn leaf blight overtook southern rust as
the primary corn disease threat in Georgia. Kemerait saw yield in one
field reduced from 200 to 70 bushels per acre as a result of this
disease. "I can almost guarantee that northern corn leaf blight will
be a problem in 2010," says Kemerait. "The spores are out there now
over-wintering. You are more likely to have this problem where you
plant corn behind corn."

Kemerait also says root-knot and stubby-root nematodes are main
concerns for corn growers. Nematicide testing in recent years showed
that fumigation prior to planting helped corn growth and led to good
yield increases where nematode populations caused significant crop
damage. New seed treatments may also help corn growers for fields with
low to moderate nematode infestations.

[Byline: John Leidner]

