[2] Fusarium, maize, wheat, barley, new strain - Pacific Northwest
Date: Sat 27 Mar 2010
Source: Capital Press [edited]
<http://www.capitalpress.com/idaho/mw-Head-blight-032610-courtesy-photos>


New blight strain appears
--------------------------
Idaho farmers are taking precautions against a strain of fusarium head
blight new to the Pacific Northwest. Juliet Windes, University of
Idaho, said the new strain has been found in the Magic Valley, Idaho.

"This particular disease really likes corn, and we keep growing more
and more corn," Windes said. "When you have small grains following
corn, the risk of this disease increases tremendously." Spores can be
locally airborne, but it typically moves with the corn seed, occurring
where there's a lot of crop residue.

The new strain will cause more head blight, or scabs, on wheat and
barley than the strains already found in the region, Windes said. It
has been more prevalent in the Midwest and has appeared in Montana,
but is new to Idaho. Other locations in the Pacific Northwest could be
impacted, she said.

Windes recommends crop rotation without planting grain after corn,
destruction of residue through plowing under and fungicides. Resistant
varieties and awareness of the conditions at flowering will be key to
controlling the disease, she said.

Some toxins produced by the strain can be dangerous to humans and some
farm animals. With malt barley, it can cause gushing in beer
production, Windes said.

[Byline: Matthew Weaver]

