[3] Stripe rust, wheat - Louisiana, Texas
Date: Wed 24 Mar 2010
Source: Delta Farm Press [edited]
<http://deltafarmpress.com/wheat/wheat-stripe-rust-0324/>


Wheat: stripe rust in Louisiana
-------------------------------
In Louisiana, stripe rust is "statewide, right now," says Steve
Harrison of the LSU [Louisiana State University]. "Whether it becomes
a big issue or not, it's a little early to say." Generally, though,
"conditions have been good for stripe rust development. I expect it to
continue moving for another a couple of weeks, at least." He wasn't
surprised by stripe rust arrival.

A mid-March [2010] rust alert was issued to Arkansas producers
"because Louisiana and Texas have reported widespread stripe rust,"
says Gene Milus, University of Arkansas. "Most of ArkansasÂ’ stripe
rust inoculum probably comes from those states." In past years, "we
did a good job of eliminating the very susceptible varieties, but
someone may have planted a very susceptible variety thinking they can
get away with it."

If conditions are favorable for stripe rust, says Milus, "one
well-timed fungicide application on a 'susceptible' variety will
protect the crop from most losses. But you'll need 2 fungicide
applications to protect a 'very susceptible' variety. That's a big
difference."

[Byline: David Bennett]

