Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Northern leaf blight of maize is caused by the fungus _Setosphaeria
turcica_. Symptoms include leaf spots which may form large necrotic
areas and kill entire leaves affecting plant vigour and yield. The
disease is favoured by humidity and temperatures of 20-25 deg C (68-77
deg F). Disease management mainly uses resistant varieties or hybrids
and cultural methods (ploughing under of crop residues, crop rotation).

Southern rust of maize caused by _Puccinia polysora_ may lead to
significant losses of over 50 percent. It is favoured by warm, humid
conditions making it an important disease in tropical areas. Genetic
resistance and fungicides are mainly used in disease management.

Several species each of root-knot and stubby-root nematodes are known
to affect maize. Disease management of nematodes is difficult and
usually requires an integrated approach which may include pathogen
exclusion, resistant crop varieties and long term crop rotation.
Elimination of nematodes from infected fields is usually not possible.

Several species of fungi originally classified in the genus _Fusarium_
cause a number of head blight, stalk rot, seedling root rot, and ear
and stalk rot diseases in grain crops such as maize, wheat, barley,
rye, and oats. Pathogens affecting these hosts may be different
phylogenetic species or strains, which are often limited to particular
regions of the world. These diseases can cause yield losses of up to
45 percent in small grain crops, reduce the grade of harvested grain,
and may also contaminate the grain with fungal toxins which can
seriously affect livestock. For any given host species, only certain
fungal strains produce toxins. Disease management generally includes
timely fungicide applications and crop varieties with reduced
susceptibility.

Stripe rust (also called yellow rust) of cereals is caused by the
fungus _Puccinia striiformis_ var. _striiformis_. It causes yellow
leaf stripes and stunting of plants with yield losses of 40 to 100 per
cent. The disease affects wheat, some barley varieties, triticale, and
a number of wild grasses. Spores are wind dispersed in several cycles
during the cropping season, and the fungus survives on living host
plants generating a "green bridge" between seasons. Disease management
includes the use of resistant varieties, fungicide applications, and
control of volunteer crops.

